[2] Norovirus (suspected), hospital - UK (Scotland)
Date: Tue 20 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: icrenfrewshire.co, Tue 20 Jul 2004 [edited]
<http://icrenfrewshire.icnetwork.co.uk/news/localnews/pdenews/pdenews/tm_obj
ectid=14444732&method=full&siteid=63858&headline=hospital-sick-bug-spreads-n
ame_page.html>

Scotland: gastroenteritis outbreak in Paisley hospital still spreading
--------------------------------------------
Infection control measures stayed in place at Paisley's Royal Alexandra
Hospital (RAH) yesterday [Mon 19 Jul 2004], after the number of people
suffering from a suspected norovirus infection continued to rise. The virus
infection, which causes vomiting and diarrhea, first hit staff and patients
at the hospital more than a week ago [2nd week July 2004]. Yesterday [Mon
19 Jul 2004], managers at the RAH said 3 more patients, and another member
of the staff, were hit by the stomach complaint over the weekend. The new
figure means that more than 50 people -- 43 patients and 8 staff -- have
now fallen ill with the infection, which usually affects its victims for 2
to 3 days.
Ward 7 -- one of the hospital's care of the elderly wards -- remains closed
to new admissions as a result of the outbreak. And, a special
control-of-infection team has brought in a series of measures to try to
tackle the infection. Within the affected ward areas, only 2 visitors per
bed are being permitted, and no children under the age of 12 are being
allowed to visit. A hospital spokesperson said, "our control-of-infection
team is monitoring the outbreak on a daily basis.
